Since Jan 1- I’m doing this trick where every day I clear out my photos from that day in my phone through the years. It’s leading me to find cool photos from back in the day, then I save them in a more accessible place. I have thousands upon thousands of photos! It also makes clearing out the folder somewhat manageable instead of monumental. Duplicates and old screen shots or random photos that u don’t need any more, delete! Try it! 🤣

When conceptualizing bathrooms, I like to make all non-primary baths in the house coordinate. Sometimes I do them exactly the same. Sometimes I do the same concept with different color ways. It’s easier, and keeps the house from feeling disjointed. All of these bathrooms have tadelak walls, terrazzo floors and coordinating marble. 

This is one of my favorite bathrooms I’ve ever done 💛

The Georgia O’Keeffe home and studio at Abequiu. 🤍 The home was designed by Ms O’Keeffe in the 1940s - she lived there from 1949 until 1984. It is built in the traditional Pueblo adobe style but is distinctly modern, and still looks very contemporary (even reminds me of my house with the built in bench sofa, etc). This is the first season that the home was open to the public and we got to tour it. I’ll share more, ten photos wasn’t enough 😂

I think about this place often. In 2016 I shot collage artist Joe Dance’s Upper West Side apartment, which at the time he had lived in for 38 years. (His wife passed in 2005.) At that time I was shooting many New York home tours for my blog, and this one felt really special because of the storytelling in each piece and of the natural light and the way I shot it. It was warm and welcoming and the opposite of the antiseptic home tours we were seeing online at the time. 

I loved shooting it and plan to revisit a lot of these old shoots and tours! Hope you enjoy! More photos and commentary from Joe in stories.

2023. I looked through all my photos and let me tell you nothing happens between January and April!!!! Everything happens in summer and fall. The growing season is the best season. In 2023 I finally became a morning person. 😂 We did sunrises. We ran. We sorted cows. We worked. We moved back to NYC. We hiked. We swam. We dove off cliffs. We rode horses. We traveled. We traveled for work. We made shirts. We cooked. We grew things. 

I make bucket lists every season, but so many of these popped up unexpectedly.Can’t wait to kick ass and surprise myself in 24 😂♥️ Happy New Year! Thanks for being part of my life :)
